{{For|the current court|Borgarting Court of Appeal}} The '''Borgarting''' was one of the major popular assemblies or [[Thing (assembly)|thing]]s (''lagting'') of medieval [[Norway]]. Historically it was the site of the court and assembly for the southern coastal region of Norway from the south-eastern border with [[Sweden]], westwards to the today's [[Risør]] in [[Aust-Agder]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://snl.no/Borgarting|title= ''Borgarting''|work=Store norske leksikon|accessdate=6 April 2013|language=Norwegian}}</ref>
Borgarting was named after its seat, the town of Borg (today [[Sarpsborg]]). It was established before 1164 when it absorbed the districts [[Grenland]] and [[Telemark]]. When Norway was united as a kingdom, the first lagtings were constituted as superior regional assemblies. The ancient regional assemblies – [[Frostating]], [[Gulating]], [[Eidsivating]] and Borgarting – were eventually joined into a single [[jurisdiction]]. King [[Magnus VI of Norway|Magnus Lagabøte]] had the existing body of law put into writing (1263–1280). In 1274, Magnus promulgated the new national law (''[[Magnus Lagabøtes landslov]]''), a unified code of laws to apply for the Kingdom of Norway. This compilation of the codified [[Gulating]] laws (''Gulatingsloven'') applied throughout the realm extending to overseas possessions including the [[Faroe islands]] and [[Shetland]]. <ref>[http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Magnus_6_H%C3%A5konsson_Lagab%C3%B8te/utdypning ''Magnus 6 Håkonsson Lagabøte'' (Store norske leksikon)]</ref> <ref>[https://snl.no/Magnus_Lagab%C3%B8tes_landslov ''Magnus Lagabøtes landslov'' (Store norske leksikon)]</ref> <ref>[http://www.snl.no/Gulatingsloven ''Gulatingsloven'' (Store norske leksikon)]</ref> ==References== {{reflist}}
